fix: Implement robust script loading for installer

This commit fixes a critical bug where the installation wizard would either show a blank page or get stuck on the "Loading..." message. This was caused by a race condition with the JavaScript rendering logic.

The fix implements a more robust method for initializing the React application:
- The main installer script now exposes a global `init` function.
- An inline script is added via `wp_add_inline_script` to call this `init` function after the DOM is ready.
- A guard clause was added to check for the `wp.element` dependency before execution.

This ensures the script runs at the correct time, resolving the rendering issue.

In this section, https://github.com/PHPMailer/PHPMailer/blob/0ff2d3c8ead628df2493537d9f91db962aa47718/src/PHPMailer.php#L2838-L2860

Message types are selected based on certain other attributes. 
For example. An alt message type, is based on the fact that the message already has a "AltBody" 

If we set a Custom Header, with whatever ContentType and/or boundary, if such attributes are not set, it will go to default, and break despite both the headers and the body could be correctly formed. 

# Problem description
The problem here is that this default option doesn't leave margin for potential customizations. Current implementation forces strict elements (like AltBody), that could not necessarily align with a correctly formatted email.

# Code to reproduce
I'm coming from here on WordPress:
https://github.com/WordPress/wordpress-develop/blob/6ea383f14783604934af91c60fee9471a40974df/src/wp-includes/pluggable.php#L517-L519

As we can see in this line, what it does is the following:
- First check if it contains the multipart text in the header, and if the boundary is not empty. In this case, we have stated that this is Multipart Content Type
- Then it adds the custom header, which is the Content-Type and the boundary.  

This is sent like this to PHPMailer. PHPMailer receives this, goes to default because AltBody is probably missing, and wipes the boundary because the default condition doesn't require a boundary. 

The result: 2 `Content-Type: multipart` Headers, and the email broken.

The solution: Maybe the default condition should be a little more flexible. Currently, we are working on a patch for WordPress, to allow creating Multipart content, based on a specific body message, which has to be specifically made as an array. But for a message that is simply a string, this will always fail, regardless if the email is perfectly formatted.

Check this example: 
https://core.trac.wordpress.org/ticket/15448?replyto=70#comment:70

```
$body = '--TestBoundary
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8

This is a test email body.
--TestBoundary
Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8
<html><body>This is a test email body.</body></html>
--TestBoundary--
';
$headers = [
	'Example-Custom: value',
	'Content-Type: multipart/alternative; boundary="TestBoundary"',
];

wp_mail( 'test@example.com', 'Test', $body, $headers );
```

In this case, the email is a perfectly made `multipart/alternative`, that will send the `$body` to PHPMailer, and the headers, which are right. The only problem here is that an AltBody is missing; hence it Wil fail and result in a broken text/plain email.

comment.body:
After I was able to develop some unit tests for this PR (finally, after my testing tool with debugging was fully operative), I could discover that, in fact, PHPMailer is perfectly working and needs no changes. Despite everyone in the forums suggesting that there was a problem here, I noticed that it was completely the fault of WordPress. 

So no need for changes, everything is working as expected, I'm closing this now.
